Nuevy To-Do List

Description:
The Nuevy To-Do List project is a web application designed to help users manage their tasks effectively. The application allows users to add, edit, delete, mark as completed or uncompleted, and view tasks in a visually appealing and user-friendly interface.

Features Implemented:

Task Management:

Users can add new tasks by entering a task description in the input field and clicking the "Add Task" button.
Tasks are displayed in a list format, showing the task description, date and time of creation, and options to edit, delete, and mark as completed or uncompleted.
Local Storage:

Tasks are stored locally using the browser's local storage, ensuring that tasks persist even if the user closes the browser or refreshes the page.
The application retrieves tasks from local storage on page load, providing a seamless and continuous user experience.
User Interface:

The user interface is designed to be clean, intuitive, and responsive, offering a seamless experience across different devices and screen sizes.
Each task has a checkbox for marking it as completed or uncompleted, and completed tasks have a distinctive visual style with a light blue background and a line-through text.
Task Interaction:

Users can edit a task by clicking the "Edit" button, which opens a prompt to modify the task description.
The "Delete" button allows users to remove a task after confirming the deletion through a confirmation dialog.
Tasks can be marked as completed or uncompleted by toggling the checkbox next to each task.
Testing:

The application has been thoroughly tested to ensure that all core functionalities work as expected.
Testing includes adding tasks, editing tasks, deleting tasks, marking tasks as completed or uncompleted, and verifying the persistence of tasks through local storage.
Implementation Details:

HTML/CSS:

The HTML structure provides a foundation for the page layout.
CSS styles are applied to create an aesthetically pleasing and responsive design.
JavaScript:

The core functionalities are implemented using JavaScript.
Event listeners are employed to capture user actions, such as adding, editing, and deleting tasks.
Local storage is utilized to store and retrieve tasks.
Challenges Faced and Solutions:

DOMTokenList Error:
Initially, an error related to adding an empty class to an element was encountered.
The code was modified to add the "completed" class only when the task is completed, resolving the issue.
Conclusion:

The Nuevy To-Do List project successfully implements a feature-rich to-do list application with a focus on user experience, data persistence, and clean design. The application empowers users to manage their tasks efficiently and provides a solid foundation for future enhancements and improvements. The development process involved overcoming challenges, implementing best practices, and delivering a functional and user-friendly solution.
